## The Document That Tells the Whole Story

Day 94 completed the continuous monitoring plan — the operational schedule that converts security from a one-time setup into ongoing stewardship, with the detection versus assurance distinction at its center. The monitoring plan is the most operationally complex section of the capstone because it has to describe a program that is actually running, not one being designed from scratch.

Day 95 addresses the POA&M. I want to be direct about why the POA&M is the capstone section that most directly demonstrates what kind of security program this is — and why it deserves its own full section rather than being appended to another section as a table of open items.

The POA&M is the only document in the entire authorization package that shows the AO how the organization has managed its security obligations over time. The SSP shows what controls are implemented. The SAR shows what the assessor found. The risk register shows what risks have been identified. The POA&M shows what the organization did about the gaps that were found — which ones were remediated and when, which ones were formally accepted and why, which ones remain open and what the genuine plan is to close them.

An AO who reads the POA&M history — what was identified at assessment, what was remediated pre-authorization, what was deferred with conditions, what has been closed during the monitoring period, what is currently open, what the aging trend looks like — has a complete picture of organizational security governance. This is information that no other document provides.

