## What Actually Clicked for Me

The insight that clarified the POA&M section today is the difference between a POA&M that records history and a POA&M that tracks commitments.

A history-recording POA&M documents what was found and what has been done. It is useful as an audit trail. It answers the question "what happened?" and an auditor can reconstruct the remediation timeline from it.

A commitments-tracking POA&M documents what the organization has promised to do and holds the organization accountable to those promises. It answers the question "what is the organization obligated to do, and is it on track?" An AO who reads a commitments-tracking POA&M can tell immediately whether the organization is managing its security obligations responsibly or deferring them indefinitely.

The difference between these two is visible in two specific areas: the scheduled completion date field and the milestone structure for items that cannot be closed in a single action. An item with a scheduled completion date of "Q3 2024" that is now in Q1 2025 with no explanation has been recorded in the history-recording mode — the date was set and missed without documentation of why. An item with a missed date that includes a documented explanation ("original date missed because CP-2 Milestone 3 meeting was blocked by unavailable participant; AO notified; revised date set for 15 days after Milestone 3 completion") is being managed in the commitments-tracking mode — the organization has explained the miss, documented the revised plan, and maintained AO visibility.

The OpenMRS POA&M is managed in commitments-tracking mode. Every open item has a clear owner, a current target date, and documented milestone progress. The one missed target (CP-2 authorization condition AT RISK) has been formally communicated to the AO. This is what POA&M discipline looks like in practice.

