## POA&M Aging Analysis

The most important trend metric for POA&M health is whether closures are outpacing openings over time.

**Year one summary:**
- Items opened at assessment: 10 (POA&M-001 through POA&M-010)
- Items opened during monitoring: 3 (M-001, M-003, M-004) + 1 pending (AU-12)
- Items closed: 5 (POA&M-002, POA&M-006, POA&M-007, POA&M-010, M-001)
- Items currently open: 9 (POA&M-001, -003, -004, -005, -008, -009, M-003, M-004, AU-12 pending)

**Aging analysis:**
- Items open less than 90 days: 3 (M-003, M-004, AU-12 pending)
- Items open 90-180 days: 4 (POA&M-003, -004, -005, -008)
- Items open more than 180 days: 2 (POA&M-001 [authorization condition], POA&M-009 [decision pending])

**Assessment:** The POA&M aging is within acceptable range for a first authorization year. No item has been deferred indefinitely without explanation. The two items over 180 days both have documented status: POA&M-001 has a milestone plan with an identified blocker and AO notification; POA&M-009 has a documented decision pending with a decision timeline.

The Day 78 governance signal — items beyond 180 days without closure are a governance failure signal — applies conditionally: items beyond 180 days with documented active management and AO visibility are not governance failures; they are items in the portion of the POA&M that requires sustained organizational attention. The signal fires for items that have simply been deferred without plan.

