## What the Complete POA&M Tells the AO

An AO reading the complete POA&M history sees: 5 items closed in the first authorization year, including the most significant technical gap (POA&M-007, security group scope) and the assessment-identified training gap (POA&M-002). The continuous monitoring program produced 4 new items — including two that involved process improvements to existing controls (M-004 access review accuracy, M-003 restoration procedure currency). The program's most significant current gap (AU-12, Moderate) was self-identified by the ISSO's proactive self-assessment, not discovered by an external auditor.

This is the authorization story the POA&M tells: an organization that identifies its own gaps, closes them at a rate that keeps pace with new discoveries, manages the open items with genuine accountability, and maintains AO visibility into the items that require executive attention.

The alternative — an organization that has the same 10 items open at re-authorization as at initial authorization, with no closures and no milestone progress — tells a different and less favorable story. POA&M management discipline is how the organization demonstrates to the AO that the conditional authorization was well-placed.

