## A Real-World Example That Made This Click

The commitment-tracking value of the POA&M — showing what the organization promised to do and whether it delivered — is illustrated by the **2019 Premera Blue Cross settlement ($6.8 million)**.

The OCR investigation found that Premera had a vulnerability in its IT infrastructure that was identified during an audit in 2012 and documented in their remediation tracking. The vulnerability was not remediated. In 2015, attackers exploited the same vulnerability to breach approximately 10.4 million records.

The Premera case is exactly the failure mode that a commitments-tracking POA&M prevents. The vulnerability was documented — the history-recording function worked correctly. The remediation commitment was not tracked and enforced — the commitments-tracking function was absent. Between 2012 and 2015, the vulnerability sat in a remediation log without escalation, without milestone management, without AO visibility.

For the OpenMRS program, the Day 78 POA&M management discipline — 15-day check-in, 30-day formal status, 40-day supervisor escalation, items beyond 180 days without closure as a governance failure signal — is the operational implementation of the lesson the Premera case teaches. The POA&M is not a list of known vulnerabilities. It is an accountability system for organizational promises about managing those vulnerabilities.

